@Title { Solución para las dimensiones extendidas. Caso relativista}
@Begin
@DP
 Si partimos de la ecuación de onda para las dimensiones extendidas:
  @DP 
@Math {nabla  sup {2} Psi - {E sub {m}} over {hbar c} blbrack     {E sub {m}} over {hbar c}   - {2  alpha} over { r} brbrack Psi - {2mc sup {2}} over {hbar c} blpar {E sub {m}} over {hbar c} - {alpha} over {r} brpar Psi - blpar {alpha sup {2} } over {r sup {2} } brpar Psi= 0 }
 @DP 
 sacando factor común y reordenando tenemos:
 @DP
 @Math {nabla  sup {2} Psi - blbrack     {E sub {m} sup {2}+ 2 mc sup {2} E sub {m} } over {(hbar c) sup {2}}   - {(2 E sub {m} +2mc sup {2} ) alpha} over {hbar c r} brbrack Psi  - blpar {alpha sup {2} } over {r sup {2} } brpar Psi= 0 }
 @DP 
 aplicando el laplaciano en esféricas tenemos:
 @DP
0.8 @Scale @Math {1 over {r sup {2}} {partial} over {partial r} blpar r sup {2} {partial Psi } over {partial r} brpar + 1 over {r sup {2} Sen  theta } {partial} over {partial theta} blpar Sen theta  {partial Psi } over {partial theta} brpar  + 1 over {r sup {2} Sen sup {2} theta } {partial sup {2} Psi} over {partial phi} -  blbrack    {E sub {m} sup {2}+ 2 mc sup {2} E sub {m} } over {(hbar c) sup {2}}   - {(2 E sub {m} +2mc sup {2} ) alpha} over {hbar c r} brbrack Psi  - blpar {alpha sup {2} } over {r sup {2} } brpar Psi= 0} 
@DP 
 Si descomponemos @Math {Psi(r,theta,phi)=R(r)P(theta)T(phi) }tenemos entonces: 
 @DP
 0.8 @Scale @Math {1 over {r sup {2}} {partial} over {partial r} blpar r sup {2} R'PT brpar + 1 over {r sup {2} Sen  theta } {partial} over {partial theta} blpar Sen theta RP'T brpar  + 1 over {r sup {2} Sen sup {2} theta } RPT'' -  blbrack     {E sub {m} sup {2}+ 2 mc sup {2} E sub {m} } over {(hbar c) sup {2}}   - {(2 E sub {m} +2mc sup {2} ) alpha} over {hbar c r}brbrack RPT  - blpar {alpha sup {2} } over {r sup {2} } brpar RPT= 0}
 @DP
 Si multiplicamos por @Math {{r sup {2} Sen sup {2} theta} over {RPT}}
 @DP
 0.8 @Scale @Math {{Sen sup {2} theta } over {R} {d} over {dr} blpar r sup {2} R' brpar + {Sen theta} over {P } {d} over {d theta} blpar Sen theta P' brpar  + {T''} over {T} - r sup {2} Sen sup  {2} theta blbrack     {E sub {m} sup {2}+ 2 mc sup {2} E sub {m} } over {(hbar c) sup {2}}   - {(2 E sub {m} +2mc sup {2} ) alpha} over {hbar c r}brbrack  - r sup {2} Sen sup  {2} theta blpar {alpha sup {2} } over {r sup {2} } brpar = 0 }
@DP 
 Como tenemos un término que solo depende de @Math {phi} y la suma debe ser constante por fuerza tenemos que:
 @DP
 @Math {{T''} over {T} = cte=-m sub {l} sup {2}} con m @Sub {l }semientero.
  @DP
 Sustituyendo entonces y dividiendo por @Math { Sen sup {2} theta}
 @DP
 @Math {{1 } over {R} {d} over {dr} blpar r sup {2} R' brpar + {1 } over {P Sen theta } {d} over {d theta} blpar Sen theta P' brpar  - {m sub {l} sup {2}} over {Sen sup {2} theta} - r sup {2}  blbrack     {E sub {m} sup {2}+ 2 mc sup {2} E sub {m} } over {(hbar c) sup {2}}   - {(2 E sub {m} +2mc sup {2} ) alpha} over {hbar c r}brbrack  - alpha sup {2} = 0 }
 @DP 
 Ya tenemos separadas las variables.
 @DP
 @Math {{1 } over {R} {d} over {dr} blpar r sup {2} R' brpar  -  r sup {2}  blbrack     {E sub {m} sup {2}+ 2 mc sup {2} E sub {m} } over {(hbar c) sup {2}}   - {(2 E sub {m} +2mc sup {2} ) alpha} over {hbar c r}brbrack  = l' (l'+1) }
 @DP 
 @Math {{1 } over {P Sen theta } {d} over {d theta} blpar Sen theta P' brpar  - {m sub {l} sup {2}} over {Sen sup {2} theta} - alpha sup {2}  = -l'(l'+1) }
 @DP 
 Si llamamos @Math {alpha sup {2}-l'(l'+1)=-l(l+1)} nos quedaría:
 @DP
 @Math {{1 } over {R} {d} over {dr} blpar r sup {2} R' brpar  -  r sup {2}  blbrack     {E sub {m} sup {2}+ 2 mc sup {2} E sub {m} } over {(hbar c) sup {2}}   - {(2 E sub {m} +2mc sup {2} ) alpha} over {hbar c r}brbrack  = l' (l'+1) }                {(a')}
 @DP
 @Math {{1 } over {P Sen theta } {d} over {d theta} blpar Sen theta P' brpar  - {m sub {l} sup {2}} over {Sen sup {2} theta}  = -l(l+1) }                {(b')}
 @DP
 @Math {{T''} over {T} = cte=-m sub {l} sup {2}}                                                    {(c')}
 @DP
 La segunda ecuación solo tiene solución para l entero positivo, por tanto podemos obtener los valores de l' en función de los posibles valores de l.
 @DP
 @Math { alpha sup {2} - l' -l' sup {2} =- l(l+1) -> l' sup {2} + l'- alpha sup {2} - l(l+1)=0 }
